# AgentChattr Control Panel (ACP)

A Windows-friendly GUI (PyQt6 + QFluentWidgets) that installs, configures, and runs **agentchattr** with **Codex CLI** + **Gemini CLI**.

## What this app manages

- Clone/update `bcurts/agentchattr`
- Create/repair `agentchattr/.venv` and install Python requirements
- Detect / install Codex CLI + Gemini CLI (optional; uses `npm`)
- Workspace profiles (greenfield-friendly): pick a working directory, generate `config.toml`
- Run control: start/stop server + open wrappers (Codex/Gemini) in their own console windows
- LAN mode helpers:
  - set `server.host` to your LAN IP
  - start server with `--allow-network` when required
  - patch/unpatch `app.py` to allow LAN `Origin` (needed for non-localhost browser access)

## Requirements

- **Python 3.11+**
- Windows 10/11 recommended
- Git (for cloning/updating)
- Node.js + npm (only if you want ACP to install Codex/Gemini CLIs for you)

## Install & run (recommended)

```bat
cd /d <this-folder>
python -m venv .venv
.venv\Scripts\pip install -r requirements.txt
.venv\\Scripts\\pip install -e .
.venv\Scripts\python -m acp
```

## Notes on QFluentWidgets packages (important)

QFluentWidgets exposes the import name `qfluentwidgets`. **Do not install multiple variants at once**
(PyQt-Fluent-Widgets / PyQt6-Fluent-Widgets / PySide6-Fluent-Widgets), because they share that module name.

This project uses **PyQt6-Fluent-Widgets**.

## Licensing heads-up

- `PyQt6-Fluent-Widgets` is **GPLv3**. If you distribute ACP, you must comply with GPLv3.
  If this is a private/internal tool, you're usually fine — but don’t ship it closed-source without checking.

## Packaging

Once you're happy:

```bat
.venv\Scripts\pip install pyinstaller
.venv\Scripts\pyinstaller --noconfirm --onefile --name AgentChattrControlPanel -m acp
```

(You may want `--windowed` to hide the console.)


## Why pip prints `Obtaining file:///...`

ACP uses `pip install -e .` (editable install) so the `src/` layout imports work without copying files.
